    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-01-15T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-01-15T17:00:00-05:00" n="297"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d297">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.512/1506: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-01-15T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 15, 1938—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>46. Your 52, January 11, 10 a.m. The Department desires that you bring
                    emphatically to the attention of the Japanese authorities (<hi rend="italic"
                        >a</hi>) our interest in the consolidated taxes, pointing out that these
                    taxes are security for the cotton, wheat and flour credits of 1931 and 1933,
                    which now form a consolidated obligation of the Chinese Government held by the
                    Export-Import Bank of Washington; and (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) our insistence
                    that the Japanese authorities take no action or countenance, in areas from which
                    the legitimate Chinese authorities have withdrawn, action by any provisional
                    regime which fails adequately to take into account the aforementioned obligation
                    of the Chinese Government to the Export–Import Bank. You may add that we reserve
                    the right to hold the Japanese authorities accountable for action disregardful
                    of our interests in this matter.</p>
                <p>For your information but not for communication to the Japanese, the obligation
                    now amounts to $13,700,000, the Chinese Government having paid the installment
                    due December 31, 1937.</p>
                <p>Your 52 and the foregoing instruction have been repeated to Tokyo with
                    authorization for the Ambassador to make an approach to the Japanese Government
                    in the matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
